:::summary
Latter-day Saint philosophy is one of the most distinctive and original theological-philosophical systems in the modern world. Far from being a mere variant of Protestant Christianity, the Restoration through [Joseph Smith](article.html?id=joseph-smith) introduced a set of metaphysical, anthropological, and epistemological claims that challenge the basic assumptions of classical Western theology: that God is embodied and exalted, that matter and spirit are related forms of the same substance, that human beings are eternal intelligences now in mortal probation, and that the path of human destiny is literally to become "as God is." These claims are grounded in modern scripture and living prophets, but they also engage — and often astonish — trained philosophers.
:::

